</div>I guess we have two different ideas of what a grind is.  Back in EQ, a grind was sitting in a room pulling mobs to yourself for hours on end just for the xp.  I don't consider doing quests to be a grind.  Because I'm always being directed to do different things.  Kill different guys.  Escort people.  Ooh, now I get to summon an elite mob I needs some friends to kill!  Ooh!  Now I get to kill the Son's of Gruul and become the King of the Ogres?  Awsome!!<br />
<br />
If anything, the reason I stopped playing EQ was that, raiding had become more of a grind than actually grinding for xp.  The whole idea of...okay, we're gonna spend 6 hours in here.  We're gonna kill like 4 monsters that actually matter.  And a handful of people are gonna get some new stuff.  But 40 of us came so...hey, that was a day well spent huh?<br />
<br />
All of that &quot;joy of figuring stuff out&quot; I get just fine from dungeon bosses.  Shadow Labs in particular has some bosses you really need strategy for and everyone has to be on the ball.  But no, hey, I'd rather go fight something that takes 25 people that all have to be following the strat, and then a couple people aren't paying atten't because, ****, they've been here for 3 hours.  Then everyone dies and you get to do it again only even less people are paying attention because you've been there even LONGER.<br />
<br />
So I guess I just find it funny when a raider refers to doing quests and getting rewards for *gasp* doing a heroic task!, as grinding.<br />
<br />
<br />
